=3D"marker PREMOD1 mod-inline"></span><p class=3D"topic-paragraph"><strong>=
<span id=3D"ref1303308"></span>sodium hydroxide (NaOH)</strong>,  a corrosi=
ve white <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/crystal" class=3D"md=
-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview=3D"true">crystalline solid</a> that=
 contains the Na<sup>+</sup> (<a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science=
/sodium" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">sodium</a>) <a =
href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/cation" class=3D"md-crosslink " =
data-show-preview=3D"true">cation</a> and the OH<sup>=E2=88=92</sup> (<a hr=
ef=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/hydroxide" class=3D"md-crosslink "=
 data-show-preview=3D"true">hydroxide</a>) <a href=3D"https://www.britannic=
a.com/science/anion" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">ani=
on</a>. It readily absorbs moisture until it <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link=
 md-dictionary-tt-off eb" data-term=3D"dissolves" href=3D"https://www.brita=
nnica.com/dictionary/dissolves" data-type=3D"EB">dissolves</a>. Sodium hydr=
oxide is the most widely used industrial <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.=
com/science/alkali" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">alka=
li</a> and is often used in drain and oven cleaners. It is highly corrosive=
 to animal and vegetable <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/science/tiss=
ue" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview=3D"true">tissue</a>.=
 The alkaline solutions it forms when dissolved in <a href=3D"https://www.b=
ritannica.com/science/water" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-pre=
view=3D"true">water</a> neutralize <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/sc=
ience/acid" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">acids</a> in=
 various commercial processes. In <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/tec=
hnology/petroleum-refining" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"tr=
ue">petroleum refining</a>, it removes <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.co=
m/science/sulfuric-acid" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true"=
>sulfuric</a> and organic acids. In <a href=3D"https://www.britannica.com/s=
cience/soap" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-preview=3D"true">soapmaking<=
/a>, it acts on natural fats or oils, such as tallow or <a href=3D"https://=
www.britannica.com/science/vegetable-oil" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " =
data-show-preview=3D"true">vegetable oil</a>, to produce sodium <a href=3D"=
https://www.britannica.com/science/fatty-acid" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxr=
ef " data-show-preview=3D"true">fatty acid</a> <a href=3D"https://www.brita=
nnica.com/science/salt" class=3D"md-crosslink autoxref " data-show-preview=
=3D"true">salt</a> (soap) and glycerin (or glycerol); this saponification r=
eaction is the basis for all soapmaking.&nbsp;In <a href=3D"https://www.bri=
tannica.com/technology/papermaking" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-show-previ=
ew=3D"true">papermaking</a>, sodium hydroxide is used to break down wood in=
to pulp. Solutions of NaOH are used in the <a class=3D"md-dictionary-link m=
d-dictionary-tt-off eb" data-term=3D"treatment" href=3D"https://www.britann=
ica.com/dictionary/treatment" data-type=3D"EB">treatment</a> of <a href=3D"=
https://www.britannica.com/science/cellulose" class=3D"md-crosslink " data-=
show-preview=3D"true">cellulose</a> and in the manufacture of many chemical=
s.</p><!--[MOD1]--><span class=3D"marker MOD1 mod-inline"></span></section>=
